      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "I got a bit carried away with the goblin analogies. Let me break it down for you in a more straightforward way.\n\nThe pitot tube works by measuring the pressure difference between the free-stream air (the air flowing over the wing) and the static air (the air in stillness, usually measured at the aircraft's nose). The free-stream air pressure is higher than the static air pressure due to the wing's motion, creating a pressure differential.\n\nThe pitot tube is typically connected to a static port, which measures the static air pressure. The pressure difference between the two ports is then used to calculate the airspeed using Bernoulli's principle, which states that the pressure of a fluid (in this case, air) decreases as its velocity increases.\n\nThe pitot tube is usually designed to be a one-way valve, allowing air to flow in but not out. This ensures that the pressure measurement is accurate and not affected by any backflow or turbulence. If the pitot tube becomes blocked, the airspeed reading will be inaccurate, and the aircraft's performance will be compromised.\n\nTo illustrate this, imagine a narrow, winding tunnel that funnels air into a small chamber, where the pressure is measured. If the tunnel becomes c",
